'''Ernest Oswald Blamires''' (11 June 1881 &ndash; 6 June 1963) was a [[New Zealand]] [[first-class cricket]]er and [[clergyman]].

==Early life and clerical career==
Ernest Blamires was born in [[Warrnambool]], [[Australia]], and went to school at [[Wesley College (Victoria)|Wesley College]] in [[Melbourne]], which was then a [[Methodist]] school for boys. He went into commerce on leaving school, but in 1903 he followed his father to New Zealand and became a Methodist [[Minister (Christianity)|minister]].<ref>''[[NZ Truth]]'', 21 March 1925, p. 11.</ref>

He served as a minister for the next 56 years.<ref>''[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]'' 1964, p. 945.</ref> In [[World War I]] he served as a chaplain to the New Zealand forces at [[Gallipoli Campaign|Gallipoli]].<ref>[http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/name-130069.html Reverend E.O. Blamires]</ref> He was General Secretary of the New Zealand Bible in Schools League<ref>''Upper Hutt Leader'', 2 November 1939, p. 1.</ref> and wrote the book ''A Christian Core for New Zealand Education'' (1960).

His four elder brothers were all ministers.<ref>''[[Marlborough Express]]'', 31 October 1910, p. 6.</ref> One, [[Henry Blamires|Henry]], played first-class cricket for [[Hawke's Bay cricket team|Hawke's Bay]].

==Cricket career==
A hard-hitting batsman, known as "The Cricketing Cleric",<ref>''[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]'' 1964, p. 945.</ref> Ernest Blamires played for a number of teams as he moved around New Zealand in his work as a minister.<ref>''[[NZ Truth]]'', 21 March 1925, p. 11.</ref> He played five first-class matches for [[Wellington cricket team|Wellington]] in 1911-12 and 1912–13,<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/21/21476/First-Class_Matches.html First-class matches played by Ernest Blamires]</ref> captaining the team in one match.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/8/8610.html Wellington v Canterbury 1911-12]</ref>

While working at [[Hawera]] he played for the [[South Taranaki]] team in 1913-14 and 1914–15, twice in the [[Hawke Cup]] and once against the touring [[Australia cricket team|Australians]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/21/21476/Miscellaneous_Matches.html Miscellaneous matches played by Ernest Blamires]</ref> He played for [[Waikato]] in the Hawke Cup in 1921-22, and for a [[Taranaki Region|Taranaki]] and [[Wanganui]] team against [[Marylebone Cricket Club|MCC]] in 1922-23.

Transferring to [[Dunedin]], he resumed his first-class career at the age of 42, playing for [[Otago cricket team|Otago]] in the 1923-24 season. In his first match, batting at number four, he made 35 and 133 in a victory over [[Canterbury cricket team|Canterbury]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/11/11024.html Canterbury v Otago 1923-24]</ref> When Otago played the touring [[New South Wales cricket team]] he made 33 and 67 as an opener, and he was selected to play for [[New Zealand cricket team|New Zealand]] in their second match against New South Wales. Batting at number three, he made a [[Pair (cricket)|pair]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/11/11052.html New Zealand v New South Wales, Wellington 1923-24]</ref>

He was appointed to captain Otago in 1924-25, and led them to their first [[Plunket Shield]] championship. Batting at number six, he made 117 in 183 minutes in the match against Wellington.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/11/11401.html Wellington v Otago 1924-25]</ref> He continued to captain the side in 1925-26 and 1926–27, when he played his last first-class match.

He continued playing cricket for some years. In 1929-30 he top-scored for [[Wairarapa]] against [[English cricket team in New Zealand in 1929–30|MCC]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/131/131839.html Wairarapa v MCC 1929-30]</ref>

[[Dick Brittenden]] described him as "an excellent bat" and "a cricketer of considerable resource, [who] once, when playing [[Warwick Armstrong]]'s [[leg theory]], changed from right-hand to left-hand briefly, the better to cope with the situation"<ref>R.T. Brittenden, ''Great Days in New Zealand Cricket'', A.H. & A.W. Reed, Wellington, 1958, p. 47.</ref> &ndash; an early example of the [[switch hit]].

